WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.210 --> 00:00:05.450
Prof: So we want to
understand diffraction patterns.

00:00:05.450 --> 00:00:08.744
It's clear that there's some
relationship between the

00:00:08.744 --> 00:00:12.355
arrangement of the electrons
that are doing the scattering

00:00:12.355 --> 00:00:15.270
and the pattern of the
scattering you get.

00:00:15.270 --> 00:00:15.690
Right?
 

00:00:15.690 --> 00:00:19.335
At a particular angle there's a
particular intensity,

00:00:19.335 --> 00:00:23.400
and it must depend on how those
electrons are arranged.

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:26.960
But how is the
interesting question.

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:31.405
So what we're going to do now
is look just a little bit-- --

00:00:31.405 --> 00:00:34.570
no one figures this out,
in a real case;

00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:37.680
people have written fancy
computer programs to do this.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:42.294
But so that it doesn't seem
mysterious, I want you to get

00:00:42.294 --> 00:00:44.520
the idea of how it works.
 

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:50.210
Okay, so the first slide we
showed,

00:00:50.210 --> 00:00:53.260
or the third slide actually
that we showed last time,

00:00:53.260 --> 00:00:56.060
was made of a bunch of these
things we call benzenes,

00:00:56.060 --> 00:01:02.051
the collections of six dots,
and they're all oriented the

00:01:02.051 --> 00:01:04.980
same way;
that's not very reasonable

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:09.153
except when they get regular in
a crystal, which is where we're

00:01:09.153 --> 00:01:09.760
going.
 

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:11.980
But anyhow, if you have a whole
bunch of them,

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:17.435
but randomly distributed,
it turns out the intensity you

00:01:17.435 --> 00:01:20.867
get is stronger,
proportional to the number of

00:01:20.867 --> 00:01:22.790
them that are doing the
scattering.

00:01:22.790 --> 00:01:23.519
Right?
 

00:01:23.519 --> 00:01:27.110
But the pattern you get is the
same you'd get from just one.

00:01:27.110 --> 00:01:29.569
So that's why we use this funny
slide.

00:01:29.569 --> 00:01:31.670
And this was the pattern that
came out,

00:01:31.670 --> 00:01:34.129
this thing that looked a little
bit like a snowflake,

00:01:34.129 --> 00:01:38.947
and I'd like you to understand
why that hexagon of dots gives a

00:01:38.947 --> 00:01:39.879
snowflake.
 

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:45.150
So we take the hexagon of dots,
and what do we look for to see

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:49.730
where scattering might be,
to see-- -- what's the-- --

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:52.410
remember what the trick is?
 

00:01:52.410 --> 00:01:58.458
The trick is to look at things
that lie on equally spaced

00:01:58.458 --> 00:01:59.430
planes.
 

00:01:59.430 --> 00:02:04.614
Try to choose a set of planes
so that as many of the electrons

00:02:04.614 --> 00:02:09.544
as there are will fall on or
near that set of evenly spaced

00:02:09.544 --> 00:02:10.479
planes.
 

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:14.645
So And this is two dimensions,
so we're looking for lines,

00:02:14.645 --> 00:02:17.348
or cross-sections of planes,
right?

00:02:17.348 --> 00:02:22.671
So how can we draw lines on
here, evenly spaced lines,

00:02:22.671 --> 00:02:26.788
so that all the dots will fall
on them?

00:02:26.788 --> 00:02:30.949
Well we can do it this way,
right?

00:02:30.949 --> 00:02:33.586
So they're evenly spaced,
three of them,

00:02:33.586 --> 00:02:36.628
and all the electrons fall on
or near them.

00:02:36.628 --> 00:02:39.008
Notice, they don't have to fall
exactly on,

00:02:39.008 --> 00:02:41.400
because if they're displaced a
little bit,

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:44.740
the phase of the wave will
change a little bit,

00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:46.699
compared to the others;
but only a little bit.

00:02:46.699 --> 00:02:49.120
So it just has to be near,
not exactly on.

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:52.038
Okay, so there we have it.
 

00:02:52.038 --> 00:02:56.587
Now, so that means that you'll
get scattering in that

00:02:56.587 --> 00:03:01.050
direction, where they will
reinforce one another.

00:03:01.050 --> 00:03:09.556
Let's go back to the display we
were looking at before,

00:03:09.556 --> 00:03:10.659
here.
 

00:03:10.659 --> 00:03:11.658
Okay?
 

00:03:11.658 --> 00:03:13.770
We were talking about this just
as class started.

00:03:13.770 --> 00:03:16.872
So a wave comes in,
makes these things all move up

00:03:16.872 --> 00:03:19.280
and down, the electrons,
here and here,

00:03:19.280 --> 00:03:20.610
at the same time.
 

00:03:20.610 --> 00:03:23.745
Actually, let's make all three
of them vibrate for current

00:03:23.745 --> 00:03:24.349
purposes.
 

00:03:24.349 --> 00:03:25.710
Okay.
 

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:29.369
Now we're interested at what
angles light can come out and

00:03:29.369 --> 00:03:32.899
all these things will help each
other out, reinforce one

00:03:32.899 --> 00:03:33.669
another.
 

00:03:33.669 --> 00:03:37.049
So as we go here and look at
that vertical line,

00:03:37.049 --> 00:03:40.860
we see that they're not all
in-phase at that angle.

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:45.615
But as we increase the angle,
when we get to say here,

00:03:45.615 --> 00:03:47.590
it looks not so bad.
 

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:50.705
The top and the bottom are
actually exactly in-phase,

00:03:50.705 --> 00:03:53.222
but the middle one is exactly
out-of-phase,

00:03:53.222 --> 00:03:55.440
and it'll cancel out the top
one.

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:58.280
And if there were a whole row
of these,

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:02.240
the second one cancels the
first, the fourth would cancel

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:04.519
the third,
the sixth would cancel the

00:04:04.519 --> 00:04:07.032
fifth, and so on;
there wouldn't be anything

00:04:07.032 --> 00:04:07.758
coming out.
 

00:04:07.758 --> 00:04:10.740
And now we go a little bit away
from that.

00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:12.878
And it's worth making a point
here.

00:04:12.878 --> 00:04:16.684
Suppose that this were a very,
very, very long line of

00:04:16.684 --> 00:04:18.120
scatterers, right?
 

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:21.466
And the first two-- -- let's
get to this place here where

00:04:21.466 --> 00:04:25.367
they're all exactly in-phase;
that'll obviously be a very

00:04:25.367 --> 00:04:26.430
strong angle.
 

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:29.754
But suppose we looked at
another angle that was close to

00:04:29.754 --> 00:04:31.750
that, but just a teeny bit off.
 

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:36.079
So the first two are off by
just 1° in-phase,

00:04:36.079 --> 00:04:40.050
and the next one's off by
2° in-phase;

00:04:40.050 --> 00:04:42.379
not much off, okay?
 

00:04:42.379 --> 00:04:45.497
So are we going to get pretty
strong light coming out from

00:04:45.497 --> 00:04:45.879
that?
 

00:04:45.879 --> 00:04:46.949
Russell?
 

00:04:46.949 --> 00:04:50.759
Student:  If it's a very
long string, you'll eventually

00:04:50.759 --> 00:04:53.103
get one that-- --
Prof: If it's a very

00:04:53.103 --> 00:04:56.170
long string,
if the first one's 1° out,

00:04:56.170 --> 00:04:59.845
by the time we get to the
180th, it'll be 180°

00:04:59.845 --> 00:05:02.129
out,
or exactly-- -- so the 180th

00:05:02.129 --> 00:05:06.288
will cancel the first one,
the 181st will cancel the

00:05:06.288 --> 00:05:10.319
second, the 182nd will cancel
the third,

00:05:10.319 --> 00:05:10.889
and so on.
 

00:05:10.889 --> 00:05:12.300
Right?
 

00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:16.480
So it has to-- -- if you have a
really long string,

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:19.899
it has to be exactly on,
from one to the next,

00:05:19.899 --> 00:05:23.540
in order to get them so that
you get something coming out.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:26.112
And what you get coming out
then will be quite strong

00:05:26.112 --> 00:05:29.230
because it'll be the scattering
from the whole bunch of them.

00:05:29.230 --> 00:05:31.290
Right?
 

00:05:31.290 --> 00:05:35.339
Where did you see that in last
week's lecture,

00:05:35.339 --> 00:05:37.050
Friday's lecture?
 

00:05:37.050 --> 00:05:38.389
Student:  In the dots.
 

00:05:38.389 --> 00:05:41.562
Prof: Right,
you saw it that you got very

00:05:41.562 --> 00:05:45.139
fine dots when you had a really
long row of things.

00:05:45.139 --> 00:05:53.709
Okay, so back to here.
 

00:05:53.709 --> 00:05:57.040
So there'll be things that are
almost exactly in-phase,

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:59.589
and it'll be a certain angle at
which they'll be in-phase,

00:05:59.589 --> 00:06:02.850
and that angle is shown by the
end of that arrow,

00:06:02.850 --> 00:06:04.860
and you get,
therefore, a dot there,

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:09.569
and also, by symmetry,
the other five of the six dots;

00:06:09.569 --> 00:06:12.529
but you could draw the lines
other angles the same way.

00:06:12.529 --> 00:06:16.259
Everybody with me on that?
 

00:06:16.259 --> 00:06:21.303
Okay, now so we look for
electron density on or near

00:06:21.303 --> 00:06:23.579
evenly spaced planes.
 

00:06:23.579 --> 00:06:27.850
Now because it only has to be
near, there are other directions

00:06:27.850 --> 00:06:31.209
we could draw it,
so we get a set of planes where

00:06:31.209 --> 00:06:35.800
they're near but not on;
like here, right?

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:39.144
Now one is a little above the
plane, two are a little below

00:06:39.144 --> 00:06:42.603
the plane-- -- right?-- -- or
vice-versa for the second line,

00:06:42.603 --> 00:06:43.180
right?
 

00:06:43.180 --> 00:06:45.463
But they're pretty close,
and they're at a certain

00:06:45.463 --> 00:06:45.930
spacing.
 

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:51.480
Now, that spacing is larger
than the blue spacing.

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:53.569
Does everybody see that?
 

00:06:53.569 --> 00:06:57.242
What does that mean about the
angle at which the reflection

00:06:57.242 --> 00:07:00.980
will occur, or the scattering,
where they'll be in phase?

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:02.220
Students:  Smaller.
 

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:04.379
Prof: The angle will be
smaller.

00:07:04.379 --> 00:07:09.711
So the part of the snowflake
that comes from that is here,

00:07:09.711 --> 00:07:10.459
right?
 

00:07:10.459 --> 00:07:14.050
A smaller angle because it's a
larger distance.

00:07:14.050 --> 00:07:16.160
And you can see immediately why
that is,

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:20.192
if we look at this thing,
that if you look at the top to

00:07:20.192 --> 00:07:22.271
the bottom,
where they're far apart,

00:07:22.271 --> 00:07:26.081
the lines are far apart,
you get the first reflection

00:07:26.081 --> 00:07:26.750
there.
 

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:30.038
But if the lines are closer
together, like these two,

00:07:30.038 --> 00:07:34.021
then you have to go to a higher
angle in order to get that first

00:07:34.021 --> 00:07:36.110
one, first coming into phase.
 

00:07:36.110 --> 00:07:37.209
Right?
 

00:07:37.209 --> 00:07:41.819
So that's that reciprocal
relationship.

00:07:41.819 --> 00:07:44.144
Okay, so we get a set of six
dots like that,

00:07:44.144 --> 00:07:45.930
and that's most of the pattern.
 

00:07:45.930 --> 00:07:48.240
But there are other places too
you can see it.

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:52.319
For example,
you can take those lines.

00:07:52.319 --> 00:07:56.690
In that set of lines,
every-- -- the center of every

00:07:56.690 --> 00:07:58.319
dot is on a line.
 

00:07:58.319 --> 00:08:01.122
There happens to be a line in
the middle that doesn't have

00:08:01.122 --> 00:08:03.870
anything on it;
but who cares?

00:08:03.870 --> 00:08:04.629
Right?
 

00:08:04.629 --> 00:08:07.560
The others are on evenly spaced
lines.

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:08.019
Right?
 

00:08:08.019 --> 00:08:09.129
So they'll all be in-phase.
 

00:08:09.129 --> 00:08:12.480
Where will that one come,
that reflection,

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:14.279
close in or far out?
 

00:08:14.279 --> 00:08:14.778
Students:  Far out.
 

00:08:14.778 --> 00:08:16.603
Prof: Far out,
and there you see it,

00:08:16.603 --> 00:08:17.560
way out at the edge.
 

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:18.259
Can you see it there?
 

00:08:18.259 --> 00:08:20.680
Just a little bit with-- -- I
could turn the room lights down,

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:22.029
but I don't think it's worth
it.

00:08:22.029 --> 00:08:23.399
You can see that it's there.
 

00:08:23.399 --> 00:08:27.480
And so there are six of them
out there as well.

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:32.666
Okay, so you got the idea of
how by looking for evenly spaced

00:08:32.666 --> 00:08:37.852
planes you can predict what the
pattern will be for a certain

00:08:37.852 --> 00:08:40.360
arrangement of electrons.
 

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:44.399
Now, notice those ones far out
are very weak.

00:08:44.399 --> 00:08:48.938
That's because although the
centers of the dots lie right on

00:08:48.938 --> 00:08:51.274
the lines,
the lines are getting so

00:08:51.274 --> 00:08:54.726
closely spaced that there's part
of the electron density that's

00:08:54.726 --> 00:08:58.196
not right on the lines,
that in fact gets out to almost

00:08:58.196 --> 00:08:59.909
halfway between the lines.
 

00:08:59.909 --> 00:09:01.048
Right?
 

00:09:01.048 --> 00:09:04.798
And that part of the electron
density will be canceling.

00:09:04.798 --> 00:09:08.370
So most of the electron density
is all in-phase here,

00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:11.644
but some of it is out-of-phase,
and as you get the lines closer

00:09:11.644 --> 00:09:14.505
and closer together,
the fact that the electron

00:09:14.505 --> 00:09:17.952
distribution is finite,
and not tiny points,

00:09:17.952 --> 00:09:23.166
means that things will get
weaker and weaker as you go to

00:09:23.166 --> 00:09:24.750
higher angles.
 

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:28.846
Okay, so there again we notice
here that the closer spaced

00:09:28.846 --> 00:09:30.860
planes give higher angles.
 

00:09:30.860 --> 00:09:33.950
This is what we've just been
talking about.

00:09:33.950 --> 00:09:38.570
Now, when you take a slide with
a regular lattice of these

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:42.623
benzenes, then-- -- remember,
if you took just one,

00:09:42.623 --> 00:09:45.460
you get this snowflake pattern.
 

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:49.282
If you take a whole row,
across the top,

00:09:49.282 --> 00:09:55.062
like that-- -- oh pardon me,
I meant to say that one will be

00:09:55.062 --> 00:09:58.690
very weak, you can hardly see
it.

00:09:58.690 --> 00:10:00.900
What you need is a bunch of
them to cooperate,

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:02.668
to see something that you can
see.

00:10:02.668 --> 00:10:06.407
Now first we could take the
whole row along the top,

00:10:06.407 --> 00:10:10.583
and we're going to look only at
scattering in the vertical

00:10:10.583 --> 00:10:13.652
direction;
so I've narrowed in on the

00:10:13.652 --> 00:10:14.360
picture.
 

00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:17.269
But if we take that whole row
along the top,

00:10:17.269 --> 00:10:21.331
remember, they'll all scatter
in-phase at the specular angle,

00:10:21.331 --> 00:10:24.308
because-- -- for scattering up
and down.

00:10:24.308 --> 00:10:28.558
So now it gets more intense
because they're all cooperating.

00:10:28.558 --> 00:10:31.625
For other directions they
wouldn't all be in-phase from

00:10:31.625 --> 00:10:35.128
one hexagon to the next,
but for scattering up and down,

00:10:35.128 --> 00:10:38.049
where they're all at exactly
the same level,

00:10:38.049 --> 00:10:39.080
they'll all be exactly the same.
 

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:43.570
Okay, now suppose I add the
next row.

00:10:43.570 --> 00:10:48.461
Will they be in-phase,
for the same direction of

00:10:48.461 --> 00:10:53.456
scattering up and down,
where that top row is all

00:10:53.456 --> 00:10:54.808
in-phase?
 

00:10:54.808 --> 00:10:59.168
So we would get the scattering
shown here, right?

00:10:59.168 --> 00:11:02.220
Stronger than it was before
because it's a bunch of these

00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:03.309
things now, right?
 

00:11:03.309 --> 00:11:04.740
But still not really strong.
 

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:06.940
But let's add in the next row.
 

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:09.889
Is that going to make them all
stronger again?

00:11:09.889 --> 00:11:13.015
No, most of the time they'll be
out-of-phase,

00:11:13.015 --> 00:11:15.856
from the next row,
for scattering in this

00:11:15.856 --> 00:11:16.567
direction.
 

00:11:16.567 --> 00:11:17.350
Right?
 

00:11:17.350 --> 00:11:19.750
Most of the time they'll be
out-of-phase,

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:23.048
but for particular
angles they'll be in-phase.

00:11:23.048 --> 00:11:27.428
So in fact what that will do,
if we add the next row,

00:11:27.428 --> 00:11:30.743
we've made the picture brighter
because we've got twice as many

00:11:30.743 --> 00:11:35.644
things scattering now,
but there'll be bars across it,

00:11:35.644 --> 00:11:36.908
like that.
 

00:11:36.908 --> 00:11:40.616
It's always the same pattern,
getting brighter and brighter

00:11:40.616 --> 00:11:44.000
as we add more of them,
but at certain angles they're

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.440
in-phase now and at certain
angles they're out-of-phase,

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:51.960
from one pattern to the next,
or from one row to the next.

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:55.659
Now, what's going to happen if
we add the whole sheet of them?

00:11:55.659 --> 00:12:01.139
Can you see?
 

00:12:01.139 --> 00:12:01.269
Sam?
 

00:12:01.269 --> 00:12:04.408
Student:  Well you're
only going to get very thin-- --

00:12:04.408 --> 00:12:06.190
Prof: Ah,
there'll only be really

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:08.610
precise angles,
at which they all interfere;

00:12:08.610 --> 00:12:11.961
otherwise the 180th will
interfere with the first,

00:12:11.961 --> 00:12:14.355
the 181st with the second and
so on.

00:12:14.355 --> 00:12:15.038
Right?
 

00:12:15.038 --> 00:12:17.594
So if we add the whole phase,
the whole thing,

00:12:17.594 --> 00:12:20.772
then if we look at the pattern
it's going to be brighter,

00:12:20.772 --> 00:12:21.340
right?
 

00:12:21.340 --> 00:12:26.611
But it'll be only dots,
only at very precise angles.

00:12:26.611 --> 00:12:27.440
Right?
 

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:32.267
And that's what we saw when we
went to this final picture for

00:12:32.267 --> 00:12:34.519
scattering from a lattice.
 

00:12:34.519 --> 00:12:40.836
So what this means is that the
lattice repeat concentrates the

00:12:40.836 --> 00:12:45.705
snowflake scattering into
tightly focused spots,

00:12:45.705 --> 00:12:47.879
on a regular pattern.
 

00:12:47.879 --> 00:12:49.019
Right?
 

00:12:49.019 --> 00:12:57.509
So this is the diffraction from
a 2-D lattice of benzenes,

00:12:57.509 --> 00:13:01.889
which is the same as the
underlying snowflake that came

00:13:01.889 --> 00:13:05.267
from just one,
but it's as if it were being

00:13:05.267 --> 00:13:07.785
viewed,
as I said last time,

00:13:07.785 --> 00:13:09.568
through a pegboard.
 

00:13:09.568 --> 00:13:10.320
Right?
 

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:14.255
All that scattering gets
concentrated into a few points,

00:13:14.255 --> 00:13:17.120
very bright,
and these regular points.

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:19.966
Now some people seemed not to
know what a pegboard was,

00:13:19.966 --> 00:13:22.759
so I took a picture of a
pegboard over the weekend.

00:13:22.759 --> 00:13:26.107
How many people have never seen
a pegboard before,

00:13:26.107 --> 00:13:27.678
just to calibrate me?
 

00:13:27.678 --> 00:13:29.580
Okay, most people have seen a
pegboard.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:33.269
But you can put these hooks in
it and then hang whatever you

00:13:33.269 --> 00:13:36.836
want on it, like tools or
pictures or whatever you want to

00:13:36.836 --> 00:13:38.149
put on your wall.
 

00:13:38.149 --> 00:13:40.953
Okay, so it's like looking
through the holes in that,

00:13:40.953 --> 00:13:42.408
at the snowflake pattern.
 

00:13:42.408 --> 00:13:46.615
Now, there are two,
quote, spaces that get talked

00:13:46.615 --> 00:13:49.769
about: direct space or real
space;

00:13:49.769 --> 00:13:53.379
and diffraction space or
reciprocal space.

00:13:53.379 --> 00:13:53.980
Okay?
 

00:13:53.980 --> 00:13:58.509
So the crystal is the real
thing that you're interested in,

00:13:58.509 --> 00:14:02.259
and diffraction photo is in
diffraction space;

00:14:02.259 --> 00:14:05.932
you see these dots that Lowy
Laue saw, for example,

00:14:05.932 --> 00:14:07.327
for copper sulfate.
 

00:14:07.327 --> 00:14:07.990
Right?
 

00:14:07.990 --> 00:14:13.190
So in real space you have a
unit cell structure;

00:14:13.190 --> 00:14:15.836
that is, the thing,
the pattern that then gets

00:14:15.836 --> 00:14:17.659
repeated to make the crystal.
 

00:14:17.659 --> 00:14:19.700
But you have the pattern, right?
 

00:14:19.700 --> 00:14:22.087
And that gives rise to this
fuzzy pattern,

00:14:22.087 --> 00:14:24.360
like a snowflake in reciprocal
space.

00:14:24.360 --> 00:14:28.383
And then you have a crystal
lattice, a regular repetition of

00:14:28.383 --> 00:14:30.019
these patterns,
right?

00:14:30.019 --> 00:14:34.769
And that's as viewing through
the holes in the pegboard.

00:14:34.769 --> 00:14:35.850
Okay?
 

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:39.298
And remember that decreased
spacing in real space

00:14:39.298 --> 00:14:43.250
corresponds to increased spacing
in reciprocal space;

00:14:43.250 --> 00:14:46.360
which is of course why it's
called "reciprocal".

00:14:46.360 --> 00:14:49.860
Okay, so that's what we want to
understand about how it works.

00:14:49.860 --> 00:14:50.538
Right?
 

00:14:50.538 --> 00:14:53.793
There are patterns which give
rise to patterns in reciprocal

00:14:53.793 --> 00:14:55.375
space,
that fuzzy thing,

00:14:55.375 --> 00:14:58.629
and then if you have a
repeating lattice of that,

00:14:58.629 --> 00:15:01.230
it gets concentrated into
particular points;

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:02.908
but it's the same underlying
pattern.

00:15:02.908 --> 00:15:06.615
So there's the pattern,
which is the structure of the

00:15:06.615 --> 00:15:10.605
molecule, and there's the
lattice, which is the structure

00:15:10.605 --> 00:15:11.960
of the crystal.
 

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:14.230
Okay, now let's look at the
light bulb filament,

00:15:14.230 --> 00:15:17.580
the last thing we looked at,
and see why the scattering from

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:22.678
that looks the way we do--
-- looks like this X with dots

00:15:22.678 --> 00:15:23.850
along it.
 

00:15:23.850 --> 00:15:27.871
Okay, so we take-- -- we want
to find if there are electrons

00:15:27.871 --> 00:15:29.440
on this helix,
right?

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:33.145
We can find a set of evenly
spaced, parallel planes like the

00:15:33.145 --> 00:15:34.340
yellow ones here.
 

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:37.330
So we'll get scattering
perpendicular to those planes.

00:15:37.330 --> 00:15:41.350
And sure enough there it is,
that spot.

00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:46.155
But we could also take a set of
planes, and it goes not only up

00:15:46.155 --> 00:15:48.558
but also down,
both branches;

00:15:48.558 --> 00:15:52.591
both directions of that
particular branch of the X,

00:15:52.591 --> 00:15:54.850
come from the same planes.
 

00:15:54.850 --> 00:15:55.230
Okay?
 

00:15:55.230 --> 00:15:58.827
But you could make planes that
are twice as close to one

00:15:58.827 --> 00:15:59.351
another.
 

00:15:59.351 --> 00:15:59.940
Right?
 

00:15:59.940 --> 00:16:02.519
What will those give rise to?
 

00:16:02.519 --> 00:16:03.970
Student:  Further out.
 

00:16:03.970 --> 00:16:07.419
Prof: Twice as far out;
the sine is twice as big

00:16:07.419 --> 00:16:09.389
actually, not the actual
spacing.

00:16:09.389 --> 00:16:12.332
But it's that one,
the second one out along the

00:16:12.332 --> 00:16:12.909
branch.
 

00:16:12.909 --> 00:16:14.149
Okay?
 

00:16:14.149 --> 00:16:18.726
Now, will that be-- -- do you
expect that to be brighter or

00:16:18.726 --> 00:16:21.330
not as bright as the first one?
 

00:16:21.330 --> 00:16:22.788
Student:  Not as bright.
 

00:16:22.788 --> 00:16:29.070
Prof: Not-- -- well it
probably will be not as bright,

00:16:29.070 --> 00:16:31.777
and the reason is that for-- --
there are two things that have

00:16:31.777 --> 00:16:33.019
to do with the brightness.
 

00:16:33.019 --> 00:16:37.587
One is how much density there
is on the planes versus how much

00:16:37.587 --> 00:16:39.684
there is between the planes.
 

00:16:39.684 --> 00:16:40.360
Right?
 

00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:44.028
And we see here that-- -- say
take the original yellow one--

00:16:44.028 --> 00:16:47.894
-- there's a lot;
all this stuff is nearly on the

00:16:47.894 --> 00:16:52.918
plane, and halfway between the
plane there's not very much,

00:16:52.918 --> 00:16:56.470
just a thin cross-section of
the wire.

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:57.678
Okay?
 

00:16:57.678 --> 00:17:01.399
But as the planes get closer
and closer,

00:17:01.399 --> 00:17:05.932
the fact that the wire has a
finite thickness means that some

00:17:05.932 --> 00:17:09.034
parts of the wire,
the same part of the wire,

00:17:09.034 --> 00:17:11.190
are out-of-phase compared to
others.

00:17:11.190 --> 00:17:13.942
So because of the finite
thickness you expect it to

00:17:13.942 --> 00:17:16.420
slowly fall off in intensity as
you go out;

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:21.298
but you'll then get the third
one along the branch and so on.

00:17:21.298 --> 00:17:24.333
And you can do the same trick
in the other direction.

00:17:24.333 --> 00:17:24.799
Right?
 

00:17:24.799 --> 00:17:26.650
So that's why it's an X.
 

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:31.390
You can draw the analogous
mirror image lines.

00:17:31.390 --> 00:17:34.920
Okay, now what does the X,
the angle of the X tell you?

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:39.134
The X could look like this,
or it could look like this,

00:17:39.134 --> 00:17:39.759
right?
 

00:17:39.759 --> 00:17:44.019
What do you learn from that,
the angle that the X makes?

00:17:44.019 --> 00:17:46.288
Student:  How tightly
wound the helix is.

00:17:46.288 --> 00:17:48.200
Prof: How tightly wound
the helix is,

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:50.390
because if the helix were very
tight,

00:17:50.390 --> 00:17:52.348
then the planes would be like
this,

00:17:52.348 --> 00:17:55.609
and if you grabbed the spring
and stretched it out,

00:17:55.609 --> 00:17:58.200
they'd look like this. Right?
 

00:17:58.200 --> 00:18:01.901
So the angle of the X tells how
tightly wound the helix is,

00:18:01.901 --> 00:18:03.880
tells the pitch of the helix.
 

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:04.769
Okay?
 

00:18:04.769 --> 00:18:08.730
What does the spacing of the
spots tell you?

00:18:08.730 --> 00:18:11.093
Did you do the homework I
suggested for today,

00:18:11.093 --> 00:18:12.880
that you didn't have to hand
in?

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:18.618
Then you'll know what the
spacing of the spots tells you.

00:18:18.618 --> 00:18:22.586
If you know the wavelength of
the X-rays, or of the light in

00:18:22.586 --> 00:18:26.420
this case, what does the spacing
of the spots tell you?

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:29.190
Student:  The spacing of
the plane that's-- --

00:18:29.190 --> 00:18:33.498
Prof: It tells you what
the actual distance is between

00:18:33.498 --> 00:18:37.950
successive turns of the helix,
how far apart the planes are.

00:18:37.950 --> 00:18:42.098
So it tells the scale of the
helix, right?

00:18:42.098 --> 00:18:46.840
The angle you get from the X,
but how big the actual helix is

00:18:46.840 --> 00:18:50.160
you get from the spacing of
those dots,

00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:53.721
if you know the wavelength and
the distance that you're

00:18:53.721 --> 00:18:55.634
magnifying;
in the case of the

00:18:55.634 --> 00:18:58.211
demonstration,
the distance from the slide at

00:18:58.211 --> 00:19:00.848
the back of the room to the
front of the room,

00:19:00.848 --> 00:19:02.078
for seeing this.
 

00:19:02.078 --> 00:19:06.336
And the spots weaken
successively because of wire

00:19:06.336 --> 00:19:10.950
thickness, as we just explained,
as you go on out.

00:19:10.950 --> 00:19:15.545
Now, that looks very much like
Rosalind Franklin's B b-DNA

00:19:15.545 --> 00:19:17.400
photograph from 1952.
 

00:19:17.400 --> 00:19:22.693
So we see the helix and we see
how angled the successive turns

00:19:22.693 --> 00:19:27.057
of the helix are,
what the pitch of the helix is,

00:19:27.057 --> 00:19:31.892
and from the spacing of the
dots we get how big the actual

00:19:31.892 --> 00:19:32.910
helix is.
 

00:19:32.910 --> 00:19:35.920
But there's something funny.
 

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:41.380
The intensity doesn't just
evenly decease as you go out.

00:19:41.380 --> 00:19:45.851
Instead of being strong,
not quite as strong,

00:19:45.851 --> 00:19:48.900
less strong,
weaker, very weak,

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:51.644
as you go out,
it goes weak,

00:19:51.644 --> 00:19:55.710
strong, strong,
very weak, strong.

00:19:55.710 --> 00:19:56.960
Now why is that?
 

00:19:56.960 --> 00:20:01.368
Why do you get such a funny
pattern of intensities?

00:20:01.368 --> 00:20:05.420
Let's look here at this thing
again.

00:20:05.420 --> 00:20:07.532
Remember where,
if we looked at the first,

00:20:07.532 --> 00:20:10.212
second, third and so on,
we saw that they come in and

00:20:10.212 --> 00:20:11.088
out of phase.
 

00:20:11.088 --> 00:20:13.440
But let's suppose-- -- so it
would be,

00:20:13.440 --> 00:20:16.538
if you have things that are
twice as close together here,

00:20:16.538 --> 00:20:20.238
as in the first case,
what effect does that have on

00:20:20.238 --> 00:20:22.308
the actual pattern we see?
 

00:20:22.308 --> 00:20:25.868
The pattern we saw,
if we had only every other one,

00:20:25.868 --> 00:20:30.298
was here the direct beam,
first reflection,

00:20:30.298 --> 00:20:33.373
second reflection,
third reflection,

00:20:33.373 --> 00:20:35.130
fourth reflection.
 

00:20:35.130 --> 00:20:41.690
How does it differ if we add
one in between?

00:20:41.690 --> 00:20:45.980
Okay, here's the first
reflection-- -- can we see that,

00:20:45.980 --> 00:20:47.808
if we have all three.
 

00:20:47.808 --> 00:20:51.214
That's what would've been the
first reflection if we didn't

00:20:51.214 --> 00:20:52.858
have the intermediate one.
 

00:20:52.858 --> 00:20:56.848
Do we see a reflection here,
if we have a whole row of them?

00:20:56.848 --> 00:20:59.059
No, because every other one
cancels out.

00:20:59.059 --> 00:21:00.509
So we won't see that one.
 

00:21:00.509 --> 00:21:01.598
How about the next one?
 

00:21:01.598 --> 00:21:02.890
Student:  It'll be very
bright.

00:21:02.890 --> 00:21:04.813
Prof: Yes,
it'll be very bright,

00:21:04.813 --> 00:21:07.038
because there's more doing the
scattering.

00:21:07.038 --> 00:21:11.088
How about if we go to the next
one?

00:21:11.088 --> 00:21:13.549
No, nothing there,
cancelled, right?

00:21:13.549 --> 00:21:16.430
How about the next one?
 

00:21:16.430 --> 00:21:18.740
Do you perceive a pattern
emerging?

00:21:18.740 --> 00:21:19.920
What is it?
 

00:21:19.920 --> 00:21:22.589
What?
 

00:21:22.589 --> 00:21:29.365
Student: It's successive;
you see it, then you don't see

00:21:29.365 --> 00:21:29.690
it.
 

00:21:29.690 --> 00:21:32.869
Prof: Can you say it in
a more mathematical way?

00:21:32.869 --> 00:21:34.640
Suppose we numbered them.
 

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:37.078
The one straight ahead we'll
call zero;

00:21:37.078 --> 00:21:40.067
then there'll the first,
one, two, three,

00:21:40.067 --> 00:21:41.038
four, five.
 

00:21:41.038 --> 00:21:44.930
What happens when we put one in
between?

00:21:44.930 --> 00:21:48.420
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:21:48.420 --> 00:21:50.839
Prof: Is one there?
 

00:21:50.839 --> 00:21:53.460
This was one here, right?
 

00:21:53.460 --> 00:21:55.680
There was one for the top and
bottom.

00:21:55.680 --> 00:21:56.470
Is that there?
 

00:21:56.470 --> 00:21:57.140
Students:  No.
 

00:21:57.140 --> 00:21:57.980
Prof: How about two?
 

00:21:57.980 --> 00:21:58.869
Students:  Yes.
 

00:21:58.869 --> 00:21:59.869
Prof: How about three?
 

00:21:59.869 --> 00:22:00.569
Students:  No.
 

00:22:00.569 --> 00:22:01.569
Prof: No.
 

00:22:01.569 --> 00:22:02.519
How about four?
 

00:22:02.519 --> 00:22:03.519
Students:  Yes.
 

00:22:03.519 --> 00:22:05.509
Prof: What's the-- --
can you state it mathematically?

00:22:05.509 --> 00:22:07.278
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another?&gt;&gt;

00:22:07.278 --> 00:22:08.788
Prof: Lexie,
what do you say?

00:22:08.788 --> 00:22:10.900
Student:
&gt;

00:22:10.900 --> 00:22:12.009
Prof: Can't hear very
well.

00:22:12.009 --> 00:22:14.900
Student:  n+2?
 

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:16.250
Prof: Which ones
disappear?

00:22:16.250 --> 00:22:18.410
Student: Odd.
 

00:22:18.410 --> 00:22:18.858
Student:  The even.
 

00:22:18.858 --> 00:22:21.454
Prof: The odd ones,
one, three, five,

00:22:21.454 --> 00:22:23.871
seven, nine;
the odd ones disappear but the

00:22:23.871 --> 00:22:26.542
even ones are still there,
if we put an extra one in

00:22:26.542 --> 00:22:27.119
between.
 

00:22:27.119 --> 00:22:29.960
Now let's think about DNA.
 

00:22:29.960 --> 00:22:32.589
Here's a helix, right?
 

00:22:32.589 --> 00:22:34.730
But what do you say about DNA?
 

00:22:34.730 --> 00:22:36.009
Is it just a helix?
 

00:22:36.009 --> 00:22:37.108
Students:  Double helix.
 

00:22:37.108 --> 00:22:39.190
Prof: It's a double
helix, so there are two helices.

00:22:39.190 --> 00:22:42.317
Okay, so suppose we have-- --
there are the successive turns

00:22:42.317 --> 00:22:44.650
and we get scattering at a
certain angle--

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:46.880
-- but suppose we make a double
helix,

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:48.470
now what'll happen?
 

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:50.400
Lexie, you're going to help me
again.

00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:52.240
Student: Oh.
 

00:22:52.240 --> 00:22:56.190
Prof: How different will
it be if we have a second helix

00:22:56.190 --> 00:22:58.740
wound halfway between the first
helix?

00:22:58.740 --> 00:23:02.272
What will happen to the-- --
what we-- -- from one helix we

00:23:02.272 --> 00:23:03.796
had one, two,
three, four,

00:23:03.796 --> 00:23:05.989
five, six, seven,
eight, nine angles,

00:23:05.989 --> 00:23:06.720
right?
 

00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:08.368
What happens now?
 

00:23:08.368 --> 00:23:09.640
Student: You're missing
even numbers.

00:23:09.640 --> 00:23:10.150
Prof: Can't hear.
 

00:23:10.150 --> 00:23:11.410
Student:  You're missing
even numbers.

00:23:11.410 --> 00:23:12.038
Prof: Ah, !
 

00:23:12.038 --> 00:23:14.715
all the odd ones disappear.
 

00:23:14.715 --> 00:23:15.410
Right?
 

00:23:15.410 --> 00:23:18.884
So what would you have expected
to see in Rosalind Franklin's

00:23:18.884 --> 00:23:19.637
picture then?
 

00:23:19.637 --> 00:23:20.160
Right?
 

00:23:20.160 --> 00:23:22.733
It would be weak,
strong, weak,

00:23:22.733 --> 00:23:25.308
strong, weak,
strong, right?

00:23:25.308 --> 00:23:29.198
But generally getting weaker as
you go out because of the finite

00:23:29.198 --> 00:23:30.680
thickness of the wire.
 

00:23:30.680 --> 00:23:32.328
Is that what we see?
 

00:23:32.328 --> 00:23:37.326
No, we saw-- -- the first one
is very weak,

00:23:37.326 --> 00:23:41.608
strong, strong,
very weak, strong.

00:23:41.608 --> 00:23:44.470
Can you see any-- -- how could
that be?

00:23:44.470 --> 00:23:46.890
What is that telling you?
 

00:23:46.890 --> 00:23:47.358
Yes?
 

00:23:47.358 --> 00:23:48.480
Student:  They're not
perfectly in-phase.

00:23:48.480 --> 00:23:50.670
Prof: What do you mean
they're not perfectly in-phase.

00:23:50.670 --> 00:23:54.410
Student:  They're not
equally-- --

00:23:54.410 --> 00:23:55.430
Prof: Ah.
 

00:23:55.430 --> 00:24:00.144
Maybe the second one isn't
halfway between the turns of the

00:24:00.144 --> 00:24:00.958
first one.
 

00:24:00.958 --> 00:24:01.690
Right?
 

00:24:01.690 --> 00:24:03.759
What happens?
 

00:24:03.759 --> 00:24:06.119
So the planes are twice as
close there and that would

00:24:06.119 --> 00:24:08.390
cancel every other reflection,
all the odd ones.

00:24:08.390 --> 00:24:11.118
But suppose it's like that.
 

00:24:11.118 --> 00:24:15.280
Did you ever see a situation
like that before where what

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:18.609
repeats is not a line but a pair
of lines?

00:24:18.609 --> 00:24:21.278
Angela?
 

00:24:21.278 --> 00:24:22.640
Student:  The second
diffraction-- .

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:24.992
Prof: The second
diffraction pattern we looked at

00:24:24.992 --> 00:24:28.153
was of that sort,
which showed the same dots but

00:24:28.153 --> 00:24:30.380
the intensity got modulated.
 

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:32.528
Remember?
 

00:24:32.528 --> 00:24:36.482
Okay, so let's,
instead of doing this where we

00:24:36.482 --> 00:24:41.314
have equally spaced ones,
let's do one where they're not

00:24:41.314 --> 00:24:43.950
