00:25:22.433 --> 00:25:22.990
way.
 

00:25:22.990 --> 00:25:25.669
How about the first reflection
there, is that going to be

00:25:25.669 --> 00:25:26.099
strong?
 

00:25:26.099 --> 00:25:27.440
Students:  No.
 

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:30.165
Prof: No,
because this one is canceling

00:25:30.165 --> 00:25:30.470
it.
 

00:25:30.470 --> 00:25:33.276
And remember,
there's also one like this

00:25:33.276 --> 00:25:35.528
below this one;
remember, it's a really long

00:25:35.528 --> 00:25:36.298
row of these things.
 

00:25:36.298 --> 00:25:38.450
So it gets almost perfectly
cancelled;

00:25:38.450 --> 00:25:40.720
not quite because it's not
quite-- --

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:42.558
there would be exactly the
minimum,

00:25:42.558 --> 00:25:44.808
and when the first and the
third are in-phase,

00:25:44.808 --> 00:25:47.210
the second one is not exactly
out-of-phase,

00:25:47.210 --> 00:25:49.519
but very close;
very weak, that reflection's

00:25:49.519 --> 00:25:50.250
going to be.
 

00:25:50.250 --> 00:25:53.487
Now let's go to what would be
the second reflection of the

00:25:53.487 --> 00:25:54.680
single helix there.
 

00:25:54.680 --> 00:25:56.150
How about there?
 

00:25:56.150 --> 00:25:57.529
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:25:57.529 --> 00:25:59.207
Prof: Yes,
the second one now is helping

00:25:59.207 --> 00:26:01.378
out a little bit;
not perfectly but it's-- -- in

00:26:01.378 --> 00:26:04.435
fact, probably if we go just a
little bit further maybe it'd be

00:26:04.435 --> 00:26:04.930
better.
 

00:26:04.930 --> 00:26:06.970
But anyhow there'd be a
reflection there.

00:26:06.970 --> 00:26:07.578
Okay?
 

00:26:07.578 --> 00:26:12.088
Now how about if we go to the
third?

00:26:12.088 --> 00:26:15.038
That's as good as the second
one, right?

00:26:15.038 --> 00:26:17.568
And how about if we go to the
fourth?

00:26:17.568 --> 00:26:19.715
Would the fourth-- -- if they
were evenly spaced,

00:26:19.715 --> 00:26:21.460
what would you expect for the
fourth?

00:26:21.460 --> 00:26:22.190
Student:  Very strong.
 

00:26:22.190 --> 00:26:23.549
Prof: Very strong, right?
 

00:26:23.549 --> 00:26:27.420
So let's go to the fourth;
one, two, three, four.

00:26:27.420 --> 00:26:28.640
What should it be?
 

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:29.440
Students:  Really weak.
 

00:26:29.440 --> 00:26:30.720
Prof: Really weak.
 

00:26:30.720 --> 00:26:32.109
And how about the fifth?
 

00:26:32.109 --> 00:26:34.369
Students:  Strong.
 

00:26:34.369 --> 00:26:35.890
Student:  Really strong.
 

00:26:35.890 --> 00:26:37.939
Prof: That's precisely
what she saw,

00:26:37.939 --> 00:26:38.328
right?
 

00:26:38.328 --> 00:26:41.731
Weak, strong,
strong, very weak,

00:26:41.731 --> 00:26:42.720
strong.
 

00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:46.496
So that's how much,
this is how much it's offset

00:26:46.496 --> 00:26:50.113
from the center,
in order to get that sequence

00:26:50.113 --> 00:26:51.640
of intensities.
 

00:26:51.640 --> 00:26:53.940
Everybody with me on this?
 

00:26:53.940 --> 00:27:00.450
Okay.
 

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:03.098
So that's that repeated pair
pattern that we saw before.

00:27:03.098 --> 00:27:07.387
And there you see that the
outer coil of the DNA,

00:27:07.387 --> 00:27:12.034
which has phosphorous in it,
with a lot of electrons,

00:27:12.034 --> 00:27:15.338
that's very much like this
helix.

00:27:15.338 --> 00:27:18.200
Okay, much more electron
density near these planes than

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:20.160
between them,
than halfway between.

00:27:20.160 --> 00:27:22.970
But there's also much more
electron density on those,

00:27:22.970 --> 00:27:26.440
near those blue planes than in
between,

00:27:26.440 --> 00:27:30.200
for the same reason,
and that means that you get

00:27:30.200 --> 00:27:32.278
those spots on the side.
 

00:27:32.278 --> 00:27:36.269
That tells you the diameter of
the helix.

00:27:36.269 --> 00:27:41.021
Okay, and the things top and
bottom tell you the base

00:27:41.021 --> 00:27:42.848
stacking distance.
 

00:27:42.848 --> 00:27:45.708
Let me back up just a second to
show you what we mean,

00:27:45.708 --> 00:27:46.140
right?
 

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:48.356
So there are a bunch of
electrons here,

00:27:48.356 --> 00:27:50.632
a bunch of electrons here,
a bunch here,

00:27:50.632 --> 00:27:53.023
a bunch here,
and that gives scattering in

00:27:53.023 --> 00:27:54.250
this direction.
 

00:27:54.250 --> 00:27:57.480
So all that information-- --
the helix diameter,

00:27:57.480 --> 00:28:00.000
the fact that it's a helix,
the fact that it's a double

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.020
helix,
the fact that it's an offset

00:28:02.020 --> 00:28:04.273
double helix,
and the diameter of the

00:28:04.273 --> 00:28:07.670
cylinder, are all easily read
out if you know what you're

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:09.853
looking for;
which Crick knew,

00:28:09.853 --> 00:28:13.449
because he had been studying
helices of proteins,

00:28:13.449 --> 00:28:17.568
so he knew about-- -- he knew
from helix scattering.

00:28:17.568 --> 00:28:21.009
Okay, so knowing the molecule's
electron density,

00:28:21.009 --> 00:28:23.740
as we knew our artificial sort
of benzene,

00:28:23.740 --> 00:28:26.329
or this DNA,
it's easy to calculate the

00:28:26.329 --> 00:28:29.558
crystal's diffraction pattern,
especially if you have a

00:28:29.558 --> 00:28:32.529
computer to help you out;
but it's not an intellectual

00:28:32.529 --> 00:28:34.304
challenge, it's just work.
 

00:28:34.304 --> 00:28:34.848
Right?
 

00:28:34.848 --> 00:28:38.385
Using pretty heavy- duty math,
people got the Nobel Prize for

00:28:38.385 --> 00:28:40.976
developing it;
or a canned program,

00:28:40.976 --> 00:28:44.680
(that's what they got the Nobel
Prize for),

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:48.402
you can go the other way and go
from the X-ray pattern to what

00:28:48.402 --> 00:28:50.049
it was that was causing it.
 

00:28:50.049 --> 00:28:50.598
Right?
 

00:28:50.598 --> 00:28:53.617
What we did was go from what's
causing it to the pattern,

00:28:53.617 --> 00:28:56.635
but in fact you can go the
other way now when you press a

00:28:56.635 --> 00:28:57.930
button on a machine.
 

00:28:57.930 --> 00:29:05.278
And you get out the electron
density at every point in space.

00:29:05.278 --> 00:29:08.390
Okay, that's the yield from an
X-ray structure.

00:29:08.390 --> 00:29:12.009
Why don't you get the nuclear
positions, why do you get the

00:29:12.009 --> 00:29:13.318
electron positions?
 

00:29:13.318 --> 00:29:15.869
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:29:15.869 --> 00:29:17.319
Prof: Alex?
 

00:29:17.319 --> 00:29:18.038
Can't hear.
 

00:29:18.038 --> 00:29:19.279
Student:  It's too big
to diffract.

00:29:19.279 --> 00:29:20.840
Prof: Yes,
it's too heavy,

00:29:20.840 --> 00:29:23.865
so it doesn't vibrate,
the nuclei, so they don't

00:29:23.865 --> 00:29:26.724
function as an antenna,
to give off the new waves the

00:29:26.724 --> 00:29:27.828
way the electrons do.
 

00:29:27.828 --> 00:29:31.130
Okay, so you get a result,
which you can plot on a map.

00:29:31.130 --> 00:29:34.617
Now in the olden days when I
started doing this kind of

00:29:34.617 --> 00:29:37.556
thing,
the kind of map you got out was

00:29:37.556 --> 00:29:40.519
a big sheet of computer output
paper,

00:29:40.519 --> 00:29:44.255
and it had numbers on it,
and a given piece of paper was

00:29:44.255 --> 00:29:47.380
a given slice through the
"unit cell',

00:29:47.380 --> 00:29:50.184
through the pattern,
and numbers were printed out

00:29:50.184 --> 00:29:53.866
that said what was the electron
density at that particular point

00:29:53.866 --> 00:29:54.920
on that level.
 

00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:58.298
So you had an x axis,
y axis, and at this point it

00:29:58.298 --> 00:30:00.987
was seventy-five,
forty-two, fifty-five,

00:30:00.987 --> 00:30:03.675
eighty-seven,
or whatever the number is,

00:30:03.675 --> 00:30:04.778
and so on.
 

00:30:04.778 --> 00:30:09.296
And what you do is take a felt
tip pen and connect dots of

00:30:09.296 --> 00:30:13.496
equal size, and you'd get a
contour of that particular

00:30:13.496 --> 00:30:15.160
electron density.
 

00:30:15.160 --> 00:30:18.910
And here's where that was done
for a particular compound.

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:21.843
This is taken from a book
written at that time by Stout

00:30:21.843 --> 00:30:22.548
and Jensen.
 

00:30:22.548 --> 00:30:24.766
And you drew these by hands
because you didn't have a

00:30:24.766 --> 00:30:27.281
computer that could draw-- --
that could figure out where to

00:30:27.281 --> 00:30:28.220
draw it and so on.
 

00:30:28.220 --> 00:30:32.740
So here were atoms in a
particular crystal structure.

00:30:32.740 --> 00:30:36.949
Then you had a whole bunch of
sheets of paper for different

00:30:36.949 --> 00:30:39.779
slices, through the electron
density;

00:30:39.779 --> 00:30:41.930
stack them up, right?
 

00:30:41.930 --> 00:30:44.970
Now sometimes the particular
slice you're working in went

00:30:44.970 --> 00:30:48.009
right through the middle of an
atom, so you got very high

00:30:48.009 --> 00:30:49.150
electron density.
 

00:30:49.150 --> 00:30:53.509
Sometime it just barely touched
the atom, right?

00:30:53.509 --> 00:30:57.326
So you see here that that one,
that atom, this particular

00:30:57.326 --> 00:31:01.142
slice, was very near the
nucleus, so we got high electron

00:31:01.142 --> 00:31:01.960
density.
 

00:31:01.960 --> 00:31:04.388
But that one,
the nucleus was not in this

00:31:04.388 --> 00:31:07.670
plane, so you just got a little
glancing blow at it.

00:31:07.670 --> 00:31:08.278
Okay?
 

00:31:08.278 --> 00:31:13.239
But you could draw these things
on acetate or plastic sheets and

00:31:13.239 --> 00:31:15.048
stack them up,
right?

00:31:15.048 --> 00:31:19.367
So this was the model made for
the first determination of the

00:31:19.367 --> 00:31:25.481
structure of penicillin;
in fact, the potassium salt of

00:31:25.481 --> 00:31:27.180
penicillin.
 

00:31:27.180 --> 00:31:29.990
Where's the potassium atom?
 

00:31:29.990 --> 00:31:34.154
How can you distinguish
potassium from nitrogen or

00:31:34.154 --> 00:31:36.788
carbon or hydrogen or oxygen?
 

00:31:36.788 --> 00:31:37.588
Student:  Electron
density.

00:31:37.588 --> 00:31:41.410
Prof: It'll have a lot
more electron density.

00:31:41.410 --> 00:31:42.720
So do you see it?
 

00:31:42.720 --> 00:31:45.440
There's the potassium,
lots of density.

00:31:45.440 --> 00:31:51.230
Okay, now here's a molecule
that happened to be flat.

00:31:51.230 --> 00:31:55.438
So it was possible to slice
through practically all the

00:31:55.438 --> 00:31:56.140
nuclei.
 

00:31:56.140 --> 00:32:00.403
It's not a very common type of
molecule, but this one is,

00:32:00.403 --> 00:32:01.470
rubofusarin.
 

00:32:01.470 --> 00:32:05.162
Okay, now these contours are
drawn at intervals of one

00:32:05.162 --> 00:32:07.113
electron per cubic angstrom.
 

00:32:07.113 --> 00:32:07.740
Right?
 

00:32:07.740 --> 00:32:10.250
So the first one is one
electron per cubic angstrom,

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:12.810
two electrons per cubic
angstrom, three electrons per

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:14.240
cubic angstrom and so on.
 

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:18.730
Now there are both carbons and
oxygens in this.

00:32:18.730 --> 00:32:21.568
How can you tell which ones are
oxygens?

00:32:21.568 --> 00:32:24.549
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:32:24.549 --> 00:32:25.440
Prof: Yeah, Yoounjoou?
 

00:32:25.440 --> 00:32:27.167
Student:  They are more
electronegative,

00:32:27.167 --> 00:32:28.710
so they should have more
contour lines.

00:32:28.710 --> 00:32:30.618
Prof: They should have
more contour lines.

00:32:30.618 --> 00:32:33.393
So if we look here,
we see that that one goes up to

00:32:33.393 --> 00:32:35.390
five electrons per cubic
angstrom;

00:32:35.390 --> 00:32:37.916
one, two, three,
four, five rings,

00:32:37.916 --> 00:32:38.529
right?
 

00:32:38.529 --> 00:32:42.493
That one goes up to seven
electrons per cubic angstrom,

00:32:42.493 --> 00:32:43.669
and so do those.
 

00:32:43.669 --> 00:32:44.329
Right?
 

00:32:44.329 --> 00:32:47.819
So those are the oxygens.
 

00:32:47.819 --> 00:32:48.490
Okay?
 

00:32:48.490 --> 00:32:51.896
And there's a picture of the
structure and you see indeed

00:32:51.896 --> 00:32:53.480
those atoms are oxygens.
 

00:32:53.480 --> 00:32:59.769
Now, what is our fundamental
goal of looking at this stuff,

00:32:59.769 --> 00:33:02.480
what do we want to see?
 

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:03.299
Students:  Bonds.
 

00:33:03.299 --> 00:33:03.980
Prof: Bonds.
 

00:33:03.980 --> 00:33:05.059
Do you see bonds?
 

00:33:05.059 --> 00:33:07.798
What does it look like?
 

00:33:07.798 --> 00:33:12.220
It looks like just a bunch of
balls, just atoms put there.

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:15.420
Was Lewis right?
 

00:33:15.420 --> 00:33:19.851
Are there electron pairs
halfway between the bonded

00:33:19.851 --> 00:33:20.559
atoms?
 

00:33:20.559 --> 00:33:25.630
No, it's just atoms.
 

00:33:25.630 --> 00:33:26.950
Okay.
 

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:30.190
Why are there no hydrogens?
 

00:33:30.190 --> 00:33:32.058
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:33:32.058 --> 00:33:34.267
Prof: Because they have
hardly any electrons compared to

00:33:34.267 --> 00:33:34.980
the others, right?
 

00:33:34.980 --> 00:33:38.319
So they're a very weak thing.
 

00:33:38.319 --> 00:33:41.059
Okay, now those are bonds.
 

00:33:41.059 --> 00:33:43.009
You can see them there.
 

00:33:43.009 --> 00:33:44.710
Where did those lines come from?
 

00:33:44.710 --> 00:33:47.608
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another?&gt;&gt;

00:33:47.608 --> 00:33:48.650
Prof: Angela,
what did you say?

00:33:48.650 --> 00:33:50.109
Student:  Someone drew
them.

00:33:50.109 --> 00:33:51.009
Prof: Yes, you drew them.
 

00:33:51.009 --> 00:33:53.240
How did you know where to draw
the bonds?

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:54.660
Student:  You connect
the dots.

00:33:54.660 --> 00:33:57.161
Prof: You connect the
centers of the rings,

00:33:57.161 --> 00:33:57.569
right?
 

00:33:57.569 --> 00:33:58.538
Those are the bonds.
 

00:33:58.538 --> 00:34:01.134
Now how do you know what's a
single bond, what's a double

00:34:01.134 --> 00:34:02.480
bond, what's a triple bond?
 

00:34:02.480 --> 00:34:05.750
Student: More density?
 

00:34:05.750 --> 00:34:08.019
Prof: You notice in the
structure here,

00:34:08.019 --> 00:34:10.342
on the bottom right,
there are double bonds and

00:34:10.342 --> 00:34:11.199
single bonds.
 

00:34:11.199 --> 00:34:13.030
How do I know which is which?
 

00:34:13.030 --> 00:34:13.760
Is there any way of knowing?
 

00:34:13.760 --> 00:34:14.199
Elizabeth?
 

00:34:14.199 --> 00:34:15.230
Student:  Maybe the
distance between.

00:34:15.230 --> 00:34:16.340
Prof: Ah, the distance!
 

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:18.550
Double bonds should be shorter
than single bonds.

00:34:18.550 --> 00:34:22.916
And, in fact,
notice that here we have short,

00:34:22.916 --> 00:34:25.300
long and intermediate.
 

00:34:25.300 --> 00:34:27.219
Why intermediate?
 

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:30.789
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:34:30.789 --> 00:34:34.340
Prof: Why do I draw a
dotted line there?

00:34:34.340 --> 00:34:37.659
Student: 
&gt;

00:34:37.659 --> 00:34:40.739
Prof: Because we have
this, look here;

00:34:40.739 --> 00:34:42.780
resonance, right?
 

00:34:42.780 --> 00:34:46.840
So there are one- and- a- half
bonds.

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:48.989
Right?
 

00:34:48.989 --> 00:34:53.739
Okay, but fundamentally what we
see are spherical atoms,

00:34:53.739 --> 00:34:54.429
right?
 

00:34:54.429 --> 00:35:02.000
No bonds, no unshared pairs on
oxygen, just atoms.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:06.340
So was Lewis way off base?
 

00:35:06.340 --> 00:35:10.695
Actually you can see the bonds
with X-ray, but you don't look

00:35:10.695 --> 00:35:14.760
at total electron density the
way we're looking at it.

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:18.210
What you look at is difference
density;

00:35:18.210 --> 00:35:23.224
you see how different is
the picture I actually determine

00:35:23.224 --> 00:35:27.922
from what I would've expected if
they were truly just

00:35:27.922 --> 00:35:30.550
spherical atoms,
undistorted.

00:35:30.550 --> 00:35:37.170
How do you find-- -- how would
you make such a map?

00:35:37.170 --> 00:35:40.164
So you have these pieces of
paper that say how much the

00:35:40.164 --> 00:35:43.050
electron density would be at all
different points;

00:35:43.050 --> 00:35:46.150
experimentally,
how much it is experimentally.

00:35:46.150 --> 00:35:49.273
Now I want to see how different
is that from if I just had

00:35:49.273 --> 00:35:50.590
spheres for the atoms.
 

00:35:50.590 --> 00:35:53.070
What would I do?
 

00:35:53.070 --> 00:35:55.853
I have to find out what the
spheres would look like,

00:35:55.853 --> 00:35:59.182
what density they would predict
at all these different points,

00:35:59.182 --> 00:36:00.329
and then do what?
 

00:36:00.329 --> 00:36:01.210
Student:  Subtract.
 

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:04.219
Prof: Subtract, right?
 

00:36:04.219 --> 00:36:06.260
So that's the difference
density.

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:10.119
Sometimes it's called
deformation because it's

00:36:10.119 --> 00:36:13.978
how much the electron
distribution gets deformed when

00:36:13.978 --> 00:36:15.389
bonds get made.
 

00:36:15.389 --> 00:36:17.980
Okay, so you take the observed
electron density,

00:36:17.980 --> 00:36:19.550
which is from X-ray,
which is experimental,

00:36:19.550 --> 00:36:21.949
and you subtract atomic
electron density,

00:36:21.949 --> 00:36:23.969
which you calculate somehow.
 

00:36:23.969 --> 00:36:26.289
You know what spherical atoms
would look like;

00:36:26.289 --> 00:36:29.186
we'll get to that next,
how you would know what that

00:36:29.186 --> 00:36:29.469
is.
 

00:36:29.469 --> 00:36:31.210
But anyhow, how do you know
where to--

00:36:31.210 --> 00:36:33.641
-- when you're going to do the
subtraction you have to make

00:36:33.641 --> 00:36:35.320
sure you position the atoms
properly,

00:36:35.320 --> 00:36:37.320
to be subtracted, right?
 

00:36:37.320 --> 00:36:40.119
How do you know where to put
them?

00:36:40.119 --> 00:36:42.463
How do you know where to put
your spherical atoms so that you

00:36:42.463 --> 00:36:43.010
subtract it?
 

00:36:43.010 --> 00:36:43.670
Yes?
 

00:36:43.670 --> 00:36:45.159
Student:  On the center
of the rings.

00:36:45.159 --> 00:36:48.505
Prof: You put it on the
center of those rings,

00:36:48.505 --> 00:36:49.018
right?
 

00:36:49.018 --> 00:36:51.119
Okay, so let's look at a case
like this.

00:36:51.119 --> 00:36:55.719
This was done by Leiserowitz
and Ziva Berkovitch-Yellin

00:36:55.719 --> 00:36:57.849
thirty-three years ago.
 

00:36:57.849 --> 00:37:01.603
So this is an interesting
molecule because it has lots of

00:37:01.603 --> 00:37:04.820
different kinds of bonds in it:
single bonds,

00:37:04.820 --> 00:37:07.940
double bonds-- -- in fact three
double bonds in a row--

00:37:07.940 --> 00:37:12.090
-- and also benzene rings that
have these resonance bonds.

00:37:12.090 --> 00:37:15.057
Okay, so we're going to look
first at one of the benzene

00:37:15.057 --> 00:37:15.489
rings.
 

00:37:15.489 --> 00:37:15.969
Okay?
 

00:37:15.969 --> 00:37:20.487
So this map that I'm showing
you here is a difference density

00:37:20.487 --> 00:37:20.940
map.
 

00:37:20.940 --> 00:37:23.282
It's the total,
minus what it would be for the

00:37:23.282 --> 00:37:23.699
atoms.
 

00:37:23.699 --> 00:37:27.849
But notice what was subtracted
is just the carbon density;

00:37:27.849 --> 00:37:30.429
didn't subtract hydrogens.
 

00:37:30.429 --> 00:37:32.699
So let's look at the features
that are big here.

00:37:32.699 --> 00:37:36.159
This is how the electron
density changed in forming the

00:37:36.159 --> 00:37:37.570
molecule from atoms.
 

00:37:37.570 --> 00:37:38.469
Okay?
 

00:37:38.469 --> 00:37:39.768
So first look up there.
 

00:37:39.768 --> 00:37:43.240
There are some very dense
contours, right in the middle up

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:46.590
there, and that's the hydrogen
which was not subtracted,

00:37:46.590 --> 00:37:47.199
right?
 

00:37:47.199 --> 00:37:51.541
So it's the biggest game left
in town, once you've subtracted

00:37:51.541 --> 00:37:53.280
the spherical carbons.
 

00:37:53.280 --> 00:37:58.945
Okay, so that's-- -- and the
total amount of intensity in

00:37:58.945 --> 00:38:04.610
that region is one electron,
which is what you expect.

00:38:04.610 --> 00:38:08.121
Now the total amount of
deformation density in this

00:38:08.121 --> 00:38:11.561
region, where there's a single
carbon-carbon bond,

00:38:11.561 --> 00:38:13.949
is only 1/10th of an electron.
 

00:38:13.949 --> 00:38:17.079
What would Lewis have said?
 

00:38:17.079 --> 00:38:19.849
Two electrons,
it's 1/10th of an electron.

00:38:19.849 --> 00:38:23.820
Okay, now let's slice that-- --
and within the carbon-carbon

00:38:23.820 --> 00:38:26.242
bonds of the ring,
the aromatic ones,

00:38:26.242 --> 00:38:27.320
it's bigger.
 

00:38:27.320 --> 00:38:29.300
Why bigger?
 

00:38:29.300 --> 00:38:31.599
Because it's partially double
bond in the resonance

00:38:31.599 --> 00:38:32.518
structures, right?
 

00:38:32.518 --> 00:38:35.420
Okay, so it's 0.2 electrons for
those ones in the ring.

00:38:35.420 --> 00:38:41.590
Now let's slice it and turn it
so we can see its cross-section.

00:38:41.590 --> 00:38:46.630
And it's round;
no surprise there.

00:38:46.630 --> 00:38:52.840
But let's slice the ones in the
ring and turn them.

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:57.119
It's oval, not round,
the bonds are not round.

00:38:57.119 --> 00:38:58.590
Why?
 

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:01.389
Students: Ï€ bonds.
 

00:39:01.389 --> 00:39:03.608
Prof: Ah,
because they're partially made

00:39:03.608 --> 00:39:06.356
up of these p orbitals
that point in and out of the

00:39:06.356 --> 00:39:08.880
ring,
that distort it from being

00:39:08.880 --> 00:39:09.429
round.
 

00:39:09.429 --> 00:39:13.052
Okay, now let's look at the
double bonds that are in the

00:39:13.052 --> 00:39:15.159
middle of this molecule,
okay?

00:39:15.159 --> 00:39:17.681
First that one;
we've already seen that bond

00:39:17.681 --> 00:39:20.719
before that was 0.1,
had a round cross-section.

00:39:20.719 --> 00:39:23.099
But let's look at one of the
double bonds.

00:39:23.099 --> 00:39:27.318
Not too surprisingly it has
more electron deformation

00:39:27.318 --> 00:39:29.590
density in it;
0.2, right?

00:39:29.590 --> 00:39:33.480
And the one in the middle
actually has 0.3.

00:39:33.480 --> 00:39:38.074
Now they're both double bonds,
so probably they look similar,

00:39:38.074 --> 00:39:39.989
and in a sense they do.
 

00:39:39.989 --> 00:39:42.492
If we slice the first one,
and turn it,

00:39:42.492 --> 00:39:45.260
it's oval for the same reason
as before;

00:39:45.260 --> 00:39:49.610
there's a p orbital pointing in
and out of the board,

00:39:49.610 --> 00:39:52.282
and if we look at it below,
part of the bond is caused by

00:39:52.282 --> 00:39:53.715
overlapping,
as we'll see,

00:39:53.715 --> 00:39:55.260
of those p orbitals.
 

00:39:55.260 --> 00:39:58.219
So it's got an oval,
up and down shape.

00:39:58.219 --> 00:40:00.530
How about the next one?
 

00:40:00.530 --> 00:40:06.387
If we slice it and turn it,
it's also oval in

00:40:06.387 --> 00:40:10.648
cross-section,
but perpendicular.

00:40:10.648 --> 00:40:11.980
Right?
 

00:40:11.980 --> 00:40:15.110
What do you expect the next one
would look like?

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:16.510
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:40:16.510 --> 00:40:18.547
Prof: It's symmetrical;
it'll look like the first one

00:40:18.547 --> 00:40:18.889
again.
 

00:40:18.889 --> 00:40:20.730
But here's something
interesting.

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:24.179
That cross-section of the
middle one showed the

00:40:24.179 --> 00:40:28.905
deformation due to the pink but
not the deformation showing-- --

00:40:28.905 --> 00:40:31.829
due to those neighboring blue
ones.

00:40:31.829 --> 00:40:34.722
There must be something
different about the interaction

00:40:34.722 --> 00:40:37.239
at the end and the interaction
in the middle.

00:40:37.239 --> 00:40:39.940
Does everybody see that problem?
 

00:40:39.940 --> 00:40:43.889
You might think the middle one
would be round or clover-leaf

00:40:43.889 --> 00:40:47.302
shaped, but it's not,
it's distorted in the in-plane

00:40:47.302 --> 00:40:48.239
direction.
 

00:40:48.239 --> 00:40:51.128
But to understand this,
you have to be patient and wait

00:40:51.128 --> 00:40:52.947
till next week,
or later this week,

00:40:52.947 --> 00:40:55.570
when we start getting into
quantum mechanics.

00:40:55.570 --> 00:41:01.309
But notice that it's as if the
carbons formed bent bonds.

00:41:01.309 --> 00:41:07.411
So the bonds from those central
carbons at the end go up and

00:41:07.411 --> 00:41:12.480
down, but the ones in the middle
are in- plane.

00:41:12.480 --> 00:41:15.340
Now how many electrons are
there in a bond?

00:41:15.340 --> 00:41:18.675
So here we're going to plot how
many electrons vertically,

00:41:18.675 --> 00:41:21.717
and how long the bond is,
which is related to whether

00:41:21.717 --> 00:41:23.590
it's single, double,
triple.

00:41:23.590 --> 00:41:28.016
In fact, a single bond is there;
a double bond and a triple bond

00:41:28.016 --> 00:41:29.739
have those distances.
 

00:41:29.739 --> 00:41:34.213
Now if you-- -- and in fact you
could also do a one-and-a- and a

00:41:34.213 --> 00:41:37.409
half bond, those bonds in the
benzene ring.

00:41:37.409 --> 00:41:40.300
Now what would you expect this
to be?

00:41:40.300 --> 00:41:43.625
How many electrons-- -- if you
were Lewis, how many electrons

00:41:43.625 --> 00:41:45.510
would you have in a single bond?
 

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:46.150
Students:  Two.
 

00:41:46.150 --> 00:41:46.920
Prof: Two.
 

00:41:46.920 --> 00:41:48.639
Double bond?
 

00:41:48.639 --> 00:41:50.369
Students:  Four
Prof: Four.

00:41:50.369 --> 00:41:51.119
Students:  Six.
 

00:41:51.119 --> 00:41:52.070
Prof: Six.
 

00:41:52.070 --> 00:41:52.789
Students:  Three.
 

00:41:52.789 --> 00:41:55.559
Prof: Three,
okay one and a -and-a-half.

00:41:55.559 --> 00:41:58.360
Okay, so there's what you would
expect for the plot,

00:41:58.360 --> 00:42:01.809
if Lewis was right:;
two, four, six.

00:42:01.809 --> 00:42:02.429
Okay?
 

00:42:02.429 --> 00:42:06.407
Now we can take this molecule
that we just looked at and see

00:42:06.407 --> 00:42:10.518
how much electron density there
is in each of those bonds--

00:42:10.518 --> 00:42:15.505
-- and I've color-coded it-- --
and it looks pretty darn good.

00:42:15.505 --> 00:42:16.159
Right?
 

00:42:16.159 --> 00:42:18.710
Hooray for Lewis.
 

00:42:18.710 --> 00:42:20.960
And in fact the people who did
the work,

00:42:20.960 --> 00:42:22.797
Leiserowitz and
Berkovitch-Yellin,

00:42:22.797 --> 00:42:25.914
looked at a bunch of other
structures too and added those

00:42:25.914 --> 00:42:29.407
to the same plot,
and they're not bad,

00:42:29.407 --> 00:42:32.469
except the scale is wrong.
 

00:42:32.469 --> 00:42:39.154
Instead of being two,
four, six,, which I've faded

00:42:39.154 --> 00:42:43.110
out here, it's 0.1,0.2,0.3.
 

00:42:43.110 --> 00:42:47.309
So bonds are a very minor game
in the distribution of

00:42:47.309 --> 00:42:48.280
electrons.
 

00:42:48.280 --> 00:42:50.356
Lewis, in a sense,
was sort of right,

00:42:50.356 --> 00:42:53.298
there is electron
density shifted between the

00:42:53.298 --> 00:42:55.550
atoms to hold them together,
right?

00:42:55.550 --> 00:42:58.210
But much less than pairs of
electrons.

00:42:58.210 --> 00:43:02.903
In fact, this amount of bonding
density is about 1/20th of what

00:43:02.903 --> 00:43:05.931
Lewis might have said,
but never did say,

00:43:05.931 --> 00:43:08.809
because he wasn't that
naïve.

00:43:08.809 --> 00:43:10.130
Okay?
 

00:43:10.130 --> 00:43:14.547
So instead of getting two,
you get a 20th of two;

00:43:14.547 --> 00:43:15.099
0.1.
 

00:43:15.099 --> 00:43:15.829
Okay?
 

00:43:15.829 --> 00:43:18.320
So bonding density is about
1/20th of a Lewis.

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:20.545
Incidentally,
the unit "Lewis"

00:43:20.545 --> 00:43:22.429
is used only within this class.
 

00:43:22.429 --> 00:43:24.199
Okay?
 

00:43:24.199 --> 00:43:27.559
So here's another example done
by Dunitz in Switzerland and

00:43:27.559 --> 00:43:31.614
these people who were the--
-- Schuyler Seiler and

00:43:31.614 --> 00:43:35.952
Schweizer, who were Swiss,
who were the progeny of

00:43:35.952 --> 00:43:38.809
watchmakers and people that do
very precise work;

00:43:38.809 --> 00:43:42.199
because to do this you have to
have really precise

00:43:42.199 --> 00:43:44.817
experimental work,
if you're going to subtract

00:43:44.817 --> 00:43:47.561
something from something else
and have the difference be

00:43:47.561 --> 00:43:49.929
meaningful,
when the numbers are almost

00:43:49.929 --> 00:43:51.550
precisely the same,
right?

00:43:51.550 --> 00:43:53.159
Remember we looked at the total
electron density.

00:43:53.159 --> 00:43:54.800
It looked just like spheres.
 

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:57.552
So you have to be really good
with this if you want to have

00:43:57.552 --> 00:44:00.610
this be meaningful;
and those guys were really good.

00:44:00.610 --> 00:44:03.768
This was done,
what, twenty-five years ago.

00:44:03.768 --> 00:44:06.297
So they took this molecule,
which is highly symmetric,

00:44:06.297 --> 00:44:07.110
which is great.
 

00:44:07.110 --> 00:44:11.121
Remember it's got its resonance
structure, so all the bonds

00:44:11.121 --> 00:44:14.510
around the middle are the same,
top and bottom.

00:44:14.510 --> 00:44:17.648
Okay, so we need only look at a
quarter of the molecule,

00:44:17.648 --> 00:44:20.730
or for convenience a little bit
more than a quarter.

00:44:20.730 --> 00:44:22.929
So I'll blow it up here.
 

00:44:22.929 --> 00:44:26.030
And there is the electron
difference density.

00:44:26.030 --> 00:44:30.503
So this is how the electrons
shifted during formation of the

00:44:30.503 --> 00:44:31.110
bonds.
 

00:44:31.110 --> 00:44:34.219
Okay, so there's a
carbon-carbon aromatic bond,

00:44:34.219 --> 00:44:36.405
a bond and a half,
and if you turn it and look at

00:44:36.405 --> 00:44:38.099
it,
it's distorted the way you

00:44:38.099 --> 00:44:41.380
expect, just as in the previous
experiment we talked about.

00:44:41.380 --> 00:44:44.510
Here's another one, same deal.
 

00:44:44.510 --> 00:44:47.820
Now here is a single bond,
carbon-carbon single bond.

00:44:47.820 --> 00:44:51.139
What's it going to look like in
cross-section?

00:44:51.139 --> 00:44:54.579
Prof: Round. Good.
 

00:44:54.579 --> 00:44:58.079
Now here is a carbon-nitrogen
triple bond.

00:44:58.079 --> 00:44:59.219
This is something new.
 

00:44:59.219 --> 00:45:05.429
What's it going to look like in
cross-section?

00:45:05.429 --> 00:45:11.199
Maybe like a clover-leaf, huh?
 

00:45:11.199 --> 00:45:16.469
Like that, it looks like that.
 

00:45:16.469 --> 00:45:17.570
It's round.
 

00:45:17.570 --> 00:45:21.702
It's not clover-leaf,
and it's not a diamond,

00:45:21.702 --> 00:45:24.519
it's round in cross-section.
 

00:45:24.519 --> 00:45:25.590
So we'll address that later.
 

00:45:25.590 --> 00:45:26.409
What's that?
 

00:45:26.409 --> 00:45:28.190
That's not a bond.
 

00:45:28.190 --> 00:45:29.489
Students:  Unshared pair.
 

00:45:29.489 --> 00:45:36.320
Prof: That's the
unshared pair on Nitrogen.

00:45:36.320 --> 00:45:38.619
Now what's special here?
 

00:45:38.619 --> 00:45:41.309
What are we looking at?
 

00:45:41.309 --> 00:45:44.610
We're looking at the
carbon-fluorine bond.

00:45:44.610 --> 00:45:46.693
Does it look like the
carbon-carbon bonds,

00:45:46.693 --> 00:45:47.760
or carbon-nitrogen?
 

00:45:47.760 --> 00:45:50.710
How's it different?
 

00:45:50.710 --> 00:45:53.190
There's no there, there. Right?
 

00:45:53.190 --> 00:45:56.530
There aren't any electrons
holding carbon to fluorine.

00:45:56.530 --> 00:45:59.190
What the heck is going on?
 

00:45:59.190 --> 00:46:03.239
Where is the C-F bond?
 

00:46:03.239 --> 00:46:05.989
This brings up the second great
question in the course.

00:46:05.989 --> 00:46:07.639
What's the first question?
 

00:46:07.639 --> 00:46:08.420
Students:
 How do you know?

00:46:08.420 --> 00:46:10.018
Prof: How do you
know, right?

00:46:10.018 --> 00:46:16.340
And the second question is
illustrated by this film clip.

00:46:16.340 --> 00:46:39.860
&lt;&lt;Technical
adjustments&gt;&gt;

00:46:39.860 --> 00:46:45.880
Come on baby.
 

00:46:45.880 --> 00:47:03.500
I worked hard on this.
 

00:47:03.500 --> 00:47:05.119
Okay, I'll tell you what it
says.

