Okay.
 

00:47:52.480 --> 00:47:53.780
&lt;&lt;Laughter and
applause&gt;&gt;

00:47:53.780 --> 00:47:56.780
"What do you think of
him?"

00:47:56.780 --> 00:48:00.409
"Compared with what
sir?"

00:48:00.409 --> 00:48:01.840
"Exactly."
 

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:05.697
That's the second question,
compared with what? In

00:48:05.697 --> 00:48:08.851
anything quantitative,
even many qualitative things,

00:48:08.851 --> 00:48:11.407
that's the question,
and that's why we're in

00:48:11.407 --> 00:48:13.960
problems here looking for the
C-F bond.

00:48:13.960 --> 00:48:17.610
We already saw this question
when we talked about resonance.

00:48:17.610 --> 00:48:22.900
Remember, I asserted that when
you have resonance the molecule

00:48:22.900 --> 00:48:24.809
is unusually stable.
 

00:48:24.809 --> 00:48:26.639
What should you have asked?
 

00:48:26.639 --> 00:48:27.268
Student:  Compared to
what?

00:48:27.268 --> 00:48:29.288
Prof: Compared to what?
 

00:48:29.288 --> 00:48:29.760
Right?
 

00:48:29.760 --> 00:48:33.802
In that case it turns out it's
compared to observed or

00:48:33.802 --> 00:48:35.329
calculated energy.
 

00:48:35.329 --> 00:48:37.978
Compare the observed or
calculated energy,

00:48:37.978 --> 00:48:41.338
(what really happens),
to what you would expect if it

00:48:41.338 --> 00:48:42.760
were not resonant.
 

00:48:42.760 --> 00:48:46.126
And we'll talk later about how,
on what basis,

00:48:46.126 --> 00:48:48.518
you might have an expectation.
 

00:48:48.518 --> 00:48:51.639
Now we're talking about
difference electron density.

00:48:51.639 --> 00:48:54.530
So what do we compare?
 

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:56.320
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:48:56.320 --> 00:48:58.949
Prof: We compare
experimental electron density,

00:48:58.949 --> 00:49:03.306
(or it could be calculated,
if we can use quantum mechanics

00:49:03.306 --> 00:49:06.275
to calculate it)--
, but compare experimental

00:49:06.275 --> 00:49:07.739
electron density to what?
 

00:49:07.739 --> 00:49:09.449
What have we compared it to?
 

00:49:09.449 --> 00:49:10.623
Student: 
&gt;

00:49:10.623 --> 00:49:12.387
Prof: What it would be

00:49:12.387 --> 00:49:13.583
if it were just atoms.
 

00:49:13.583 --> 00:49:14.019
Right?
 

00:49:14.019 --> 00:49:17.239
But what kind of atoms, right?
 

00:49:17.239 --> 00:49:20.581
We compare the observed or
calculated total electron

00:49:20.581 --> 00:49:23.987
density to the sum of electron
densities for a set of

00:49:23.987 --> 00:49:25.429
undistorted atoms.
 

00:49:25.429 --> 00:49:29.329
Now what's an undistorted atom?
 

00:49:29.329 --> 00:49:32.179
Okay.
 

00:49:32.179 --> 00:49:35.942
Now, to avoid Pauli problems--
-- and this isn't the time to

00:49:35.942 --> 00:49:40.199
discuss what those are,
we need to subtract not an

00:49:40.199 --> 00:49:43.699
unbiased spherical fluorine
atom,

00:49:43.699 --> 00:49:47.780
which if you count up how many
electrons there are on fluorine,

00:49:47.780 --> 00:49:50.409
each quadrant of space around
fluorine--

00:49:50.409 --> 00:49:52.860
-- of which there will be
four-- --

00:49:52.860 --> 00:49:56.791
each quadrant will have one and
three three-quarters electrons

00:49:56.791 --> 00:49:57.179
in it.
 

00:49:57.179 --> 00:49:57.760
Right?
 

00:49:57.760 --> 00:50:01.898
You multiply that by four and
you get seven electrons,

00:50:01.898 --> 00:50:05.960
which is the valence electrons
of fluorine, right?

00:50:05.960 --> 00:50:11.510
But you can't have one and
three three-quarters electrons

00:50:11.510 --> 00:50:15.375
from fluorine,
and also an electron from

00:50:15.375 --> 00:50:18.250
carbon in the same place.
 

00:50:18.250 --> 00:50:21.402
That's too many electrons in
the same place,

00:50:21.402 --> 00:50:21.989
right?
 

00:50:21.989 --> 00:50:25.797
So what you have to start with
is not an undistorted spherical

00:50:25.797 --> 00:50:28.994
fluorine atom,
but a fluorine atom that's

00:50:28.994 --> 00:50:32.592
prepared to make a bond,
which has only one electron in

00:50:32.592 --> 00:50:34.739
the region where it's going to
make a bond.

00:50:34.739 --> 00:50:39.393
So if you subtract a spherical
one, you're subtracting too much

00:50:39.393 --> 00:50:42.170
from the region of the bond,
right?

00:50:42.170 --> 00:50:45.539
So that's why you don't see any
electron density in there.

00:50:45.539 --> 00:50:48.485
So, and if you want to
understand this better than I've

00:50:48.485 --> 00:50:50.559
explained it,
go on the Web and look at

00:50:50.559 --> 00:50:52.469
Professor Dunitz explaining it.
 

00:50:52.469 --> 00:50:55.940
We have a little movie of him
talking about this particular

00:50:55.940 --> 00:50:56.539
problem.
 

00:50:56.539 --> 00:50:57.010
Okay?
 

00:50:57.010 --> 00:51:01.697
But at any rate the conclusion
of all this is that bonding

00:51:01.697 --> 00:51:04.739
density is about 1/20th of a
Lewis.

00:51:04.739 --> 00:51:05.909
All right?
 

00:51:05.909 --> 00:51:07.239
And it's time for me to quit.
 

00:51:07.239 --> 00:51:09.800
We'll go on with this next time.
 

